In the code snippet you provided, the `handleSubmit` function doesn't always have a `return` statement. This could potentially cause errors or confusion in the application. To conform to the ESLint `consistent-return` rule, we should ensure that our function returns a value in a consistent manner.

Here's an updated version of the `handleSubmit` function that ensures consistent returns:

```
const handleSubmit = async () => {
  try {
    const { isSuccessful, errorMessage, numbers } = res.data;
    if (!isSuccessful) {
      setToastMessage(errorMessage);
      trackEvent("API Key", {
        result: AMP_ENUM_RESULT.failed,
      });
      return null; // Return null to indicate failure
    }

    const numArr: string[] = Object.values(numbers);
    testNums(numArr);
    return numArr; // Return numArr to indicate success
  }
  catch(error) {
    console.error(error);
    return null; // Return null in case of any error
  }
}
```

In this updated version of the code, we added a `return null;` statement in the `if (!isSuccessful)` block to ensure that the function returns a value in case of failure. We also added a `return numArr;` statement outside the `if (!isSuccessful)` block to ensure that the function returns a value in case of success. Lastly, we added a `catch` block to catch any errors that could potentially occur in the function, and we added a `return null;` statement in the catch block to ensure that the function returns a value in case of any error.

