This code iterates over an array of `senders` objects and sorts them according to their type. To improve it using the `no-restricted-syntax` rule, we can modify it to use `Array.prototype.reduce()` instead of `for...of` loop. 

Here's the updated code: 

```
const { dedicatedSenders, sharedSenders } = senders.reduce((acc, sender) => {
  if (sender.type === "dedicated") {
    acc.dedicatedSenders.push(sender.value);
  } else if (sender.type === "shared") {
    acc.sharedSenders.push(sender.value);
  }
  return acc;
}, { dedicatedSenders: [], sharedSenders: [] });
```

In this updated code, we use `reduce` to iterate over the `senders` array and assign values to `dedicatedSenders` and `sharedSenders`. We start with an accumulator object that has `dedicatedSenders` and `sharedSenders` properties set to empty arrays and with each iteration, we check the `sender.type` property to decide which array to push the `sender.value` onto. Finally, we return the accumulator object with the updated values of the two arrays. This new code is shorter and more concise and it adheres to the `no-restricted-syntax` rule.

